    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2871881941" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2871881941" />
    <a title="Asaria" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/44427430-asaria"><img alt="Asaria" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609958434p2/44427430.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2871881941?book_show_action=true">Jun 28, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Asaria" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Asaria" href="/user/show/44427430-asaria">Asaria</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9789992195444" href="/book/show/19397772-the-bridges-of-constantine">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/44427430-asaria?shelf=2019">2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/44427430-asaria?shelf=literature-arabic">literature-arabic</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/44427430-asaria?shelf=stars-5">stars-5</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2871881941" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6674473515532102647">The Bridges of Constantine... Difficult love, it is, isn&apos;t it? It has been on my radar for at least year with one unsuccessful attempt in January. As usual, wrong book, wrong mood, wrong time. Possibly if I pushed myself, I would have disliked it for the very same reason I&apos;m giving it a high rating now. <br/><br/>It is a slow, reflective book, which takes time to immerse the reader into the content. Multilayered for sure, written in the first person too. However <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[there are hints that suggest</span></span>
  <span id="freeText6674473515532102647" style="display:none">The Bridges of Constantine... Difficult love, it is, isn't it? It has been on my radar for at least year with one unsuccessful attempt in January. As usual, wrong book, wrong mood, wrong time. Possibly if I pushed myself, I would have disliked it for the very same reason I'm giving it a high rating now. <br /><br />It is a slow, reflective book, which takes time to immerse the reader into the content. Multilayered for sure, written in the first person too. However <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[there are hints that suggest the narrator might be unreliable  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. Smart move by the author, because while she is giving answers to some arising questions, this device also can explain any contradictions that would appear in the narrative.<br /><br />The narrative itself is centered around the complicated relationship between narrator and Hayat. Somewhere around 20%, I realized that <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ in his mind she, motherland and his home city merge into one  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. In an almost Mickiewicz' way: <br />"I and fatherland are one. My name is million, cause for million I love and suffer agonies" -"Our forefathers' Eve', Adam Mickiewicz<br />Of course, Mosteghanemi doesn't go as far, but she is close. <br /><br />The book is also exploring the role of artist and literature. The concept of author-prophet isn't foreign to me. This is something Polish writers were struggling in the past. In the early XIX century, prophet-writer was someone who leads the nation forward, a spiritual leader. In positivism era, writer is an educator. <br /><br />In general, according to the principles above, author, or writer should be someone, who strive to show truth, break taboos, lead nation toward new direction. An moral authority, full of dignity, questioner of the established order. That's a great burden on any shoulder to bear, too great in my opinion.<br /><br />Overall, well translated, lyrical work. 4* upped to 5* for making me invested<br /><br />Onwards to the second book!</span>
  <a data-text-id="6674473515532102647" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

